          "body": "Esther is taken into the harem — the passive verb is deliberate — and placed in the custody of Hegai. What happens next defies the logic of the selection system: 'the young lady pleased him and found favor with him. So he quickly provided her with her cosmetics and food, gave her seven choice maids from the king's palace and transferred her and her maids to the best place in the harem' (2:9). No reason is given. The narrator is not explaining; he is pointing. The same pattern repeats in 2:15: 'Esther found favor in the eyes of all who saw her.' And again in 2:17: 'the king loved Esther more than all the women, and she found favor and kindness with him more than all the virgins.' Iain Duguid notes that the accumulation of unexplained favor is the book's characteristic way of gesturing toward divine activity without naming it. God is not mentioned in the book of Esther, but His fingerprints are on every door handle. Meanwhile, Esther navigates the preparation process with a striking restraint: 'she did not request anything except what Hegai... advised' (2:15). Every other candidate took whatever she wanted. Esther defers to the man who knows the terrain. This is not passivity — it is the wisdom of a woman who has learned that trust in the right counsel is worth more than self-assertion."
